00:00:00.790 --> 00:00:03.970
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington, DC.

00:00:19.040 --> 00:00:20.560
&gt;&gt; Francisco Macias: Good
afternoon and welcome.

00:00:20.560 --> 00:00:24.320
I'm Francisco Macias from
the Law Library of Congress.

00:00:24.320 --> 00:00:27.500
We have had a wonderful
series of events in observance

00:00:27.500 --> 00:00:29.370
of Hispanic Heritage Month.

00:00:29.370 --> 00:00:31.960
And I want to thank
all my colleagues

00:00:31.960 --> 00:00:33.260
for all the work they have done

00:00:33.260 --> 00:00:38.740
to make 2016 another successful
celebration of our heritage.

00:00:38.740 --> 00:00:41.830
Today, I believe, we are
in for a special treat.

00:00:41.830 --> 00:00:44.220
In observance of Hispanic
Heritage Month,

00:00:44.220 --> 00:00:48.770
our special guest is the
award-winning Filipino-American

00:00:48.770 --> 00:00:51.330
writer, Jon Pineda.

00:00:51.330 --> 00:00:55.800
Because now Hispanic Heritage
Month could ever be complete

00:00:55.800 --> 00:00:59.730
without talking a little
bit about the Philippines.

00:00:59.730 --> 00:01:01.990
He is the author of five books.

00:01:01.990 --> 00:01:07.130
His novel, <i>Apology </i>won the
Milkweed National Fiction Prize

00:01:07.130 --> 00:01:10.240
and his memoir, <i>Sleep
in Me </i>made the Barnes

00:01:10.240 --> 00:01:14.820
and Noble Discover Great
New Writer selection.

00:01:14.820 --> 00:01:19.240
His poetic voice captured in the
following collections, <i>Birthmark </i>,

00:01:19.240 --> 00:01:23.430
winner of the Crab Orchard
Award Series Open Competition,

00:01:23.430 --> 00:01:28.430
<i>The Translator's Diary </i>, winner
of the Green Rose Prize in Poetry

00:01:28.430 --> 00:01:34.750
and <i>Little Anodynes </i>recently named
a finalist for the 2016 Library

00:01:34.750 --> 00:01:37.950
of Virginia Literary
Award in Poetry.

00:01:37.950 --> 00:01:41.710
A core faculty member in
the low-residency Master

00:01:41.710 --> 00:01:45.450
of Fine Arts Program at Queens
University of Charlotte,

00:01:45.450 --> 00:01:48.680
Jon is Assistant Professor
of English at the University

00:01:48.680 --> 00:01:53.260
of Mary Washington and has twice
served on the teaching faculty

00:01:53.260 --> 00:01:56.820
for the Kundiman Asian-American
Poets Retreat held

00:01:56.820 --> 00:02:00.240
at Fordham University.

00:02:00.240 --> 00:02:05.460
Of his work, Oliver dela Paz
stated regardless of the distance,

00:02:05.460 --> 00:02:10.160
Jon Pineda's resolute and lyrical
language traverses the spectrum

00:02:10.160 --> 00:02:15.000
of human conditions and eases
our lonely and troubled selves

00:02:15.000 --> 00:02:17.700
into the possibility of joy.

00:02:17.700 --> 00:02:23.220
A special note of thanks goes to
Baily Slaughter for bringing Jon

00:02:23.220 --> 00:02:26.080
and his work to our attention.

00:02:26.080 --> 00:02:30.940
And now we leave Jon in the
capable hands of our colleague,

00:02:30.940 --> 00:02:34.870
Roberto Salazar, a senior
program specialist from the Office

00:02:34.870 --> 00:02:37.910
of Equal Employment Opportunity
and Diversity Programs.

00:02:37.910 --> 00:02:40.510
And now, please join me
in welcoming Jon Pineda.

00:02:40.510 --> 00:02:45.040
[ Applause ]

00:02:45.040 --> 00:02:46.340
&gt;&gt; Roberto Salazar:
Thank you, Francisco.

00:02:46.340 --> 00:02:47.640
Good afternoon.

00:02:47.640 --> 00:02:49.350
Welcome to the Library of Congress.

00:02:49.350 --> 00:02:52.760
Our program's title
today, Filipino-Americans,

00:02:52.760 --> 00:02:55.000
the other Asian Americans.

00:02:55.000 --> 00:02:59.480
When it comes to labels of
identity, we have a tendency

00:02:59.480 --> 00:03:02.310
to assume things about
others, don't we?

00:03:02.310 --> 00:03:06.010
That means that what is it that you
think other Americans should know

00:03:06.010 --> 00:03:09.230
about Filipino-Americans?

00:03:09.230 --> 00:03:10.970
&gt;&gt; Jon Pineda: Yeah, I -- well,
one of the things when I think

00:03:10.970 --> 00:03:17.570
about Filipino-Americans, the first
thing I think of is the family,

00:03:17.570 --> 00:03:18.870
the way in which

00:03:18.870 --> 00:03:20.830
so many Filipino-American
families are very welcoming

00:03:20.830 --> 00:03:22.480
and very generous.

00:03:22.480 --> 00:03:25.500
And, you know, this
isn't by any means,

00:03:25.500 --> 00:03:27.460
it doesn't make them
an exceptional group.

00:03:27.460 --> 00:03:30.540
I think there are other
cultures that do the same thing.

00:03:30.540 --> 00:03:34.990
But Filipino-American families that
I grew up around, they have lots

00:03:34.990 --> 00:03:38.670
of big parties, lots of
"lumpia," lots of "pancit,"

00:03:38.670 --> 00:03:41.710
chicken "adobo," "bibingka,"
you name it.

00:03:41.710 --> 00:03:45.720
And extended friends
were brought in,

00:03:45.720 --> 00:03:49.590
treated in some ways
as relatives as well.

00:03:49.590 --> 00:03:54.410
But as far as Filipino-Americans
in terms of their imprint

00:03:54.410 --> 00:03:58.760
on American society, I think
it's exciting when you think

00:03:58.760 --> 00:04:05.790
about how early they made
their presence known here

00:04:05.790 --> 00:04:07.710
in the United States.

00:04:07.710 --> 00:04:12.000
There's the mention of the
course of the 16th century

00:04:12.000 --> 00:04:17.890
where the Filipino Americans had
come over to California and Spain

00:04:17.890 --> 00:04:23.100
but after that, they're the first
Asian settlement, I believe,

00:04:23.100 --> 00:04:28.470
was in 1763 and it was the St.
Marlowe fishing village which is

00:04:28.470 --> 00:04:31.760
in just south of New
Orleans in Louisiana.

00:04:31.760 --> 00:04:36.710 position:56%
And it was there for almost a little
more than 150 years that it was able

00:04:36.710 --> 00:04:41.980
to remain intact until it was
destroyed by a hurricane in 1915.

00:04:41.980 --> 00:04:46.570
So the Filipino presence in
the United States is, you know,

00:04:46.570 --> 00:04:50.910 position:56%
has been here and then I should also
note that there were different waves

00:04:50.910 --> 00:04:55.730
of Filipino-American or Filipino
immigration to the United States.

00:04:55.730 --> 00:04:58.620
And so, if you meet
a Filipino, it's --

00:04:58.620 --> 00:05:01.790
you know, the first
thing I'll ask is, "Oh,

00:05:01.790 --> 00:05:03.100
you know, where are you from?"

00:05:03.100 --> 00:05:06.630
Like in the islands, because the
islands, there are 7000 islands

00:05:06.630 --> 00:05:10.990
in the archipelago and there
are over 120, I believe,

00:05:10.990 --> 00:05:12.590 position:56%
languages spoken in the Philippines.

00:05:12.590 --> 00:05:15.280
So you can -- I have seen this.

00:05:15.280 --> 00:05:18.500
I've been in situations
where a number

00:05:18.500 --> 00:05:19.880
of Filipinos are getting together

00:05:19.880 --> 00:05:24.690
and they're not necessarily
fully understanding each other

00:05:24.690 --> 00:05:26.720
because they speak
different dialects

00:05:26.720 --> 00:05:32.270 position:56%
or they speak different languages
but yet someone who would, you know,

00:05:32.270 --> 00:05:35.140
kind of see them might visually
think that they're somewhat,

00:05:35.140 --> 00:05:37.380
you know, cohesive in
the way that they look.

00:05:37.380 --> 00:05:40.920 position:56%
But actually, they're from different
regions in the Philippines.

00:05:40.920 --> 00:05:44.530
So my father is from
the island of Luzon.

00:05:44.530 --> 00:05:49.420
He's a Pampangan and grew
up kind of north of Manila.

00:05:49.420 --> 00:05:54.260
There are Filipinos,
let's say, from Mindanao

00:05:54.260 --> 00:05:58.440 position:56%
and the dialect they speak my father
wouldn't be able to understand.

00:05:58.440 --> 00:06:01.120
So that would be one of the things
that I would offer is to say

00:06:01.120 --> 00:06:03.530
that it's a small country,
the Philippines,

00:06:03.530 --> 00:06:09.010
but within that country, there's a
very large community of diversity

00:06:09.010 --> 00:06:12.300
that exists because
of the archipelago.

00:06:12.300 --> 00:06:18.080 position:56%
That translates when you think about
the immigration to the United States

00:06:18.080 --> 00:06:25.810
with let's say the "Manong"
generation in the 1915 or 1920s

00:06:25.810 --> 00:06:27.720
or so, the laborers that had come

00:06:27.720 --> 00:06:31.560
to the United States
from the Ilocano region.

00:06:31.560 --> 00:06:36.490
And typically settled
in California or Hawaii.

00:06:36.490 --> 00:06:38.130
You know, this portion

00:06:38.130 --> 00:06:41.580
of the Philippines has a
large connection there.

00:06:41.580 --> 00:06:44.330
But then on the East Coast, a lot

00:06:44.330 --> 00:06:49.250
of Filipinos came over
after World War II.

00:06:49.250 --> 00:06:54.180
So with Filipinos and their having
fought in World War II especially

00:06:54.180 --> 00:06:57.690 position:56%
because of the Japanese
occupation, I have an uncle who died

00:06:57.690 --> 00:07:00.340
in the Bataan Death March.

00:07:00.340 --> 00:07:04.250
You know, it's something that --
like, when you really are looking

00:07:04.250 --> 00:07:08.780
at the waves of immigration of
the Filipinos here, there --

00:07:08.780 --> 00:07:12.690
you can point to different regions
and then you can also look at kind

00:07:12.690 --> 00:07:19.630 position:56%
of a class system as well that you
know, the recent wave of immigration

00:07:19.630 --> 00:07:23.020
from the Philippines being
healthcare workers, doctors

00:07:23.020 --> 00:07:26.450
and nurses but prior when
the Filipinos came in

00:07:26.450 --> 00:07:28.340 position:56%
and I would say maybe the third wave

00:07:28.340 --> 00:07:31.290
after World War II,
they joined the Navy.

00:07:31.290 --> 00:07:34.320
And my father came here
because of the Navy.

00:07:34.320 --> 00:07:38.100
He was allowed to join the Navy
when he was still in the islands

00:07:38.100 --> 00:07:42.790
and then transfer here and
then went through the rigors

00:07:42.790 --> 00:07:44.130
in order to become a citizen.

00:07:44.130 --> 00:07:49.060
So that would probably be the
first thing is just to say

00:07:49.060 --> 00:07:54.390
that it's very diverse in
the scope of the community

00:07:54.390 --> 00:07:58.370
of Filipino-Americans but at the
same time, it's also very tightknit

00:07:58.370 --> 00:08:01.590
and a welcoming community too.

00:08:01.590 --> 00:08:03.110
&gt;&gt; Roberto Salazar: You
touched on this in your comment

00:08:03.110 --> 00:08:06.930
and that is the imprint of
Filipinos in the United States.

00:08:06.930 --> 00:08:11.230
It's certainly not a new imprint,
dating back to the 16th century.

00:08:11.230 --> 00:08:15.550
In fact, it was 1587,
October 18th of 1587

00:08:15.550 --> 00:08:19.470
that the first Filipino
mariners came,

00:08:19.470 --> 00:08:23.500
became the first recorded Asians,
if you will, that came to America

00:08:23.500 --> 00:08:28.100
on board what was then the Spanish
galleon named Nuestra Senora de

00:08:28.100 --> 00:08:30.930
Esperanza which as I
understand was under the command

00:08:30.930 --> 00:08:36.570
of Pedro de Unamuno at
Moral Bay, California.

00:08:36.570 --> 00:08:40.770
This was a time, of course, that
then in 1587 when California

00:08:40.770 --> 00:08:44.930
and in fact, the Philippines were
part of the kingdom of New Spain

00:08:44.930 --> 00:08:49.010
and so that certainly is a
significant historical moment

00:08:49.010 --> 00:08:50.640
for Filipino-Americans.

00:08:50.640 --> 00:08:53.320
I imagine there are
other moments of pride

00:08:53.320 --> 00:08:55.470 position:56%
for the Filipino-American community.

00:08:55.470 --> 00:08:58.040
What are some of those
moments that come to your mind?

00:08:58.040 --> 00:08:59.610
&gt;&gt; Jon Pineda: Well,
when I was growing up,

00:08:59.610 --> 00:09:02.510
my dad would talk about
Roman Gabriel.

00:09:02.510 --> 00:09:08.810
And Roman Gabriel was the MVP
of the NFL back in the late '60s

00:09:08.810 --> 00:09:12.560
and he was mestizo and so
that was the first time

00:09:12.560 --> 00:09:16.580
that in some ways the
Filipino-Americans in --

00:09:16.580 --> 00:09:20.650
well at least in the NFL, that
here is this major accomplishment

00:09:20.650 --> 00:09:22.040
that came forth.

00:09:22.040 --> 00:09:28.050
But you know, there are also
multiple situations in sports.

00:09:28.050 --> 00:09:29.750
You know, I think of that.

00:09:29.750 --> 00:09:34.950
But there are also wonderful
political leaders that have --

00:09:34.950 --> 00:09:39.980
I grew up in Virginia Beach, the
north of Virginia Beach area.

00:09:39.980 --> 00:09:44.900
So that was -- I always
saw Filipinos.

00:09:44.900 --> 00:09:48.430
And then when I moved away from
that area, I didn't see Filipinos.

00:09:48.430 --> 00:09:51.270
So I got to come to find
out that there were --

00:09:51.270 --> 00:09:55.900 position:56%
I think when I was growing up there,
there were over 30,000 Filipino

00:09:55.900 --> 00:09:59.040
or Filipino-Americans living
in that area at the time.

00:09:59.040 --> 00:10:01.710
I'm sure it's much larger now.

00:10:01.710 --> 00:10:07.680
But so I was kind of
insulated in that way.

00:10:07.680 --> 00:10:12.240
But since then, there have been
city council members, you know,

00:10:12.240 --> 00:10:15.350
House of Representatives -- those
are the ways in which, you know,

00:10:15.350 --> 00:10:22.670
other cultures have made a positive
impact on the American society.

00:10:22.670 --> 00:10:26.590
Another major thing that's
occurred in the last --

00:10:26.590 --> 00:10:34.270
I guess in the last 15 years -- 12
to 15 years is that with Kundiman,

00:10:34.270 --> 00:10:41.430
in the introduction, you know,
the greatest introduction is

00:10:41.430 --> 00:10:45.770 position:56%
that Kundiman is an
Asian-American literary organization

00:10:45.770 --> 00:10:48.680
that was started by two
Filipino-American writers,

00:10:48.680 --> 00:10:50.780
Sarah Gambito and Joseph Legaspi

00:10:50.780 --> 00:10:52.940
who are now starting
to get lots of acclaim.

00:10:52.940 --> 00:10:54.240
They're in New York.

00:10:54.240 --> 00:11:00.140
And what they did is they were
able to create a community

00:11:00.140 --> 00:11:03.480
of Filipino-American writers
who were winning prizes.

00:11:03.480 --> 00:11:06.550
A number of us were starting to
kind of get our work out there

00:11:06.550 --> 00:11:11.420
and they brought us together to
be mentors for the next generation

00:11:11.420 --> 00:11:17.490
of writers who were or are coming
up and not having to think,

00:11:17.490 --> 00:11:19.760
am I allowed to write about this?

00:11:19.760 --> 00:11:22.070
They're just writing
about their experiences.

00:11:22.070 --> 00:11:26.440
When I was first starting and
writing about being part Filipino,

00:11:26.440 --> 00:11:29.580
there was a part of me
that felt as you know,

00:11:29.580 --> 00:11:31.640 position:56%
I wondered could I write about this.

00:11:31.640 --> 00:11:36.160
And which, you know, was just
kind of showing just my lack

00:11:36.160 --> 00:11:39.800
of I would say maybe even
courage as a writer, you know.

00:11:39.800 --> 00:11:42.070
I needed to kind of
come to that on my own

00:11:42.070 --> 00:11:48.590
but Kundiman has stepped
forward and since then fellows

00:11:48.590 --> 00:11:54.110
from that program have won the Walt
Whitman Award which is, you know,

00:11:54.110 --> 00:11:55.550
from the Academy of American Poets.

00:11:55.550 --> 00:11:58.810
It's the best first book
by an American poet.

00:11:58.810 --> 00:12:03.770
They've won these national
prizes, the National Poetry Series.

00:12:03.770 --> 00:12:09.540
These are the kinds of forays
into American into kind of the --

00:12:09.540 --> 00:12:14.440
the venerated American literature.

00:12:14.440 --> 00:12:18.120
I also would say that the
Filipino-Americans were making a

00:12:18.120 --> 00:12:20.880
major, major impact.

00:12:20.880 --> 00:12:24.950 position:56%
And they're becoming professors at
other universities and they are able

00:12:24.950 --> 00:12:27.250
to kind of spread this knowledge.

00:12:27.250 --> 00:12:32.210
So that, for me, has been an
unbelievably amazing impact

00:12:32.210 --> 00:12:35.580
because these are our novelists
and our poets and, you know,

00:12:35.580 --> 00:12:37.670
our fiction writers, our
creative nonfiction writers.

00:12:37.670 --> 00:12:39.840
These are -- these are
the people that are

00:12:39.840 --> 00:12:42.690
in language humanizing the culture

00:12:42.690 --> 00:12:46.090
for a larger majority
in the readership.

00:12:46.090 --> 00:12:50.520
And I find that fascinating
and inspiring.

00:12:50.520 --> 00:12:54.210
And when I mentioned kind of my
lack of courage, it wasn't so much

00:12:54.210 --> 00:12:59.330
that I was fearful of not, you
know, of having any kind of fear

00:12:59.330 --> 00:13:01.020
but of not being able to
write about something.

00:13:01.020 --> 00:13:08.230 position:56%
I just didn't -- I didn't have
models for writing about being half.

00:13:08.230 --> 00:13:12.360
There were no books
written by mestizo poets

00:13:12.360 --> 00:13:16.890 position:56%
who were directly addressing that
or at least models that I had found.

00:13:16.890 --> 00:13:21.300
And some of my Filipino-American
writer friends would just say,

00:13:21.300 --> 00:13:23.550
well then, you write it.

00:13:23.550 --> 00:13:24.980
What are you waiting for?

00:13:24.980 --> 00:13:26.540
You write it.

00:13:26.540 --> 00:13:28.340
And I said, "Oh, yeah.

00:13:28.340 --> 00:13:29.640
That makes sense.

00:13:29.640 --> 00:13:30.940
Yeah, I'll write it."

00:13:30.940 --> 00:13:33.390
And so now it becomes, you know,
we become part of that literature.

00:13:33.390 --> 00:13:37.750
So I think that has
been a huge impact.

00:13:37.750 --> 00:13:39.180
&gt;&gt; Roberto Salazar: And
indeed, you've been one

00:13:39.180 --> 00:13:40.930
of the groundbreakers
in that regard as well.

00:13:40.930 --> 00:13:44.260
So let's talk about your writing
and your creative experience.

00:13:44.260 --> 00:13:47.790 position:56%
How has that been reflected perhaps?

00:13:47.790 --> 00:13:49.640
You know, how has it
been reflected --

00:13:49.640 --> 00:13:52.410
your experiences of
Filipino-American

00:13:52.410 --> 00:13:55.480
and what influences that
had in your creativity?

00:13:55.480 --> 00:13:58.890
&gt;&gt; Jon Pineda: It's had
a lot when I would go

00:13:58.890 --> 00:14:01.430
to these Filipino gatherings
when I was very young.

00:14:01.430 --> 00:14:06.460
We, at the time, were one of the
only families who were mixed,

00:14:06.460 --> 00:14:11.050
who were mestizo and I remember
just kind of walking around

00:14:11.050 --> 00:14:15.120
and I would just hear
different languages.

00:14:15.120 --> 00:14:16.850
You know, sometimes,
you would hear Spanish.

00:14:16.850 --> 00:14:18.150
Sometimes you would hear Tagalog.

00:14:18.150 --> 00:14:20.150
Sometimes you would
hear, you know, Visayan.

00:14:20.150 --> 00:14:24.390
I mean, not that I speak these
languages with any kind of fluency

00:14:24.390 --> 00:14:26.390
but I could recognize
certain things.

00:14:26.390 --> 00:14:29.470
And so this attention to
language grafted on --

00:14:29.470 --> 00:14:32.300
grafted on me in a very early age.

00:14:32.300 --> 00:14:37.910
Now mix in that, that my mom was
raised on a farm in North Carolina

00:14:37.910 --> 00:14:42.820
and very much from a rural
background in northeastern

00:14:42.820 --> 00:14:45.540
of Carolina dialect so
there was also a way

00:14:45.540 --> 00:14:48.220
in which I was understanding
that speakers

00:14:48.220 --> 00:14:53.740
of English given their regional
differences bring other kinds

00:14:53.740 --> 00:14:55.080
of focus.

00:14:55.080 --> 00:14:57.230
You know, they use
language differently

00:14:57.230 --> 00:14:59.820
and so I've always loved that.

00:14:59.820 --> 00:15:05.120
I've always been fascinated
by the ability to communicate

00:15:05.120 --> 00:15:09.260
and then striving to
make these connections

00:15:09.260 --> 00:15:13.140
between perhaps disparate
communities.

00:15:13.140 --> 00:15:18.140
In my situation, I was -- and
with writing, I've always found

00:15:18.140 --> 00:15:21.640
that I can have my
intention, you know,

00:15:21.640 --> 00:15:24.620
and that kind of begins
how I start writing.

00:15:24.620 --> 00:15:27.980
But it's actually once I put
the language on the page,

00:15:27.980 --> 00:15:33.330
once I have the words there then
I need to revise and see if I'm,

00:15:33.330 --> 00:15:36.950
you know, building the image
in a way that feels accessible.

00:15:36.950 --> 00:15:39.130
It's not over-intellectualized.

00:15:39.130 --> 00:15:42.310
It's not, you know, preening.

00:15:42.310 --> 00:15:46.520
It's not, you know, it's due -- I
want my poems to do certain things

00:15:46.520 --> 00:15:48.210
but most importantly,
I want my poems

00:15:48.210 --> 00:15:51.860
to have communion with the reader.

00:15:51.860 --> 00:15:58.840
So I think my Filipino background
with the Catholic Church, it --

00:15:58.840 --> 00:16:03.120 position:56%
you know, we Filipino-Americans
have a very interesting relationship

00:16:03.120 --> 00:16:04.420
with Catholicism.

00:16:04.420 --> 00:16:08.220
Not different from
other colonized areas

00:16:08.220 --> 00:16:12.620
that also have Catholicism
kind of placed on them.

00:16:12.620 --> 00:16:18.540
But a love for saints, a love for
these narratives of sacrifice.

00:16:18.540 --> 00:16:21.250
That was something that
growing up, I heard a lot about.

00:16:21.250 --> 00:16:24.600
My dad would tell me stories about
and he would smile as he would talk

00:16:24.600 --> 00:16:28.820
about these elderly women in
his village that would crawl

00:16:28.820 --> 00:16:34.380 position:56%
to the church on their knees and he
just really thought that was amazing

00:16:34.380 --> 00:16:36.430
like in terms of the
faith that they had.

00:16:36.430 --> 00:16:39.700
And so that was something
that impressed me.

00:16:39.700 --> 00:16:46.040
Another thing has been the
way in which by being mestizo,

00:16:46.040 --> 00:16:53.160 position:56%
I feel as if I am one foot in one
world and one foot in another world.

00:16:53.160 --> 00:16:55.490
But I'm never fully in one.

00:16:55.490 --> 00:17:00.710
So when I'm with my Filipino
friends, my writing friends,

00:17:00.710 --> 00:17:03.510
you know, who perhaps
might, you know,

00:17:03.510 --> 00:17:10.350 position:56%
have parents that are full Filipinos
and you know, [inaudible] this idea.

00:17:10.350 --> 00:17:11.780
I'm other.

00:17:11.780 --> 00:17:15.970
I'm part of the group and I'm not.

00:17:15.970 --> 00:17:19.470
Same goes for my friends
that might not be Filipino.

00:17:19.470 --> 00:17:23.770 position:56%
So I think that also informs my
creativity that I understand that --

00:17:23.770 --> 00:17:33.930
that alone, I have it, a different
relationship with the temporal

00:17:33.930 --> 00:17:39.120
and what's transient, what
stays, what's permanent.

00:17:39.120 --> 00:17:44.460
I'm not as interested in
dominating the idea of time.

00:17:44.460 --> 00:17:48.610
I'm much more interested in
allowing for the sense of flux.

00:17:48.610 --> 00:17:51.380
I'm much more interested
in hybridity.

00:17:51.380 --> 00:17:55.560
I love experimentation
in the hybrid forms.

00:17:55.560 --> 00:17:59.910
And identity is -- I'm
less interested in trying

00:17:59.910 --> 00:18:02.660
to harken back to a tradition.

00:18:02.660 --> 00:18:06.310 position:56%
I'll acknowledge a tradition but I'm
more interested in moving forward

00:18:06.310 --> 00:18:09.960
to where, you know, I
