00:18:20.120 --> 00:18:24.500
And so my own mestizo experience

00:18:24.500 --> 00:18:29.110
in some ways is kind of
prepared me for that.

00:18:29.110 --> 00:18:30.410
&gt;&gt; Roberto Salazar: Yes.

00:18:30.410 --> 00:18:31.710
That almost sounds
as if you've been --

00:18:31.710 --> 00:18:35.040
you've maintained this outsider
looking in perspective of sorts.

00:18:35.040 --> 00:18:36.340
&gt;&gt; Jon Pineda: Yes.

00:18:36.340 --> 00:18:38.880 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Roberto Salazar: While not
losing your identity in the culture.

00:18:38.880 --> 00:18:43.300
You touched on certainly what I
consider to be one of the impacts

00:18:43.300 --> 00:18:45.650
of Spain on the Philippines,
Catholicism.

00:18:45.650 --> 00:18:48.540
You touched on the fact that
the Philippines was part

00:18:48.540 --> 00:18:51.100
of New Spain in the 16th century.

00:18:51.100 --> 00:18:54.130
No doubt, there were many
other impacts that Spain had

00:18:54.130 --> 00:18:56.010
on the Philippines and Filipinos.

00:18:56.010 --> 00:19:00.450 position:56%
What are some of those impacts that
carry through today that are evident

00:19:00.450 --> 00:19:03.090
in Filipino and Filipino-American
culture that you've observed?

00:19:03.090 --> 00:19:06.320
&gt;&gt; Jon Pineda: Well, yes --
the impact of Spain, I think,

00:19:06.320 --> 00:19:10.440
is still present in the
names, in the language.

00:19:10.440 --> 00:19:17.960
In Tagalog, you can find words
that aren't spelled the same way

00:19:17.960 --> 00:19:23.110
as perhaps in Spanish but you
can -- when you hear the word,

00:19:23.110 --> 00:19:24.640
it's almost as if an American

00:19:24.640 --> 00:19:30.030
who doesn't speak Spanish was
phonetically writing Spanish

00:19:30.030 --> 00:19:35.140
and then you see that word
and it's a Tagalog word.

00:19:35.140 --> 00:19:39.150
That's something that kind of
sits there and ghosts its way

00:19:39.150 --> 00:19:41.070
through the Filipino culture.

00:19:41.070 --> 00:19:45.170
I find that that Spain is very
much a ghost in the language.

00:19:45.170 --> 00:19:52.640
It's also this -- the way in
which the islands were colonized

00:19:52.640 --> 00:19:57.070
and remained colonized
for over 300 years.

00:19:57.070 --> 00:20:06.420
They -- there is this interesting
situation and the Tagalogs

00:20:06.420 --> 00:20:13.250
that were the native culture
that was present in the islands

00:20:13.250 --> 00:20:21.890
when Spain arrived, the Tagalogs
already had a written script.

00:20:21.890 --> 00:20:25.270
They already had a
literature that they were --

00:20:25.270 --> 00:20:27.880
you know, they had a language.

00:20:27.880 --> 00:20:31.620
And that I believe
there's a written script.

00:20:31.620 --> 00:20:34.980
You'll hear it referenced as
Alibata which I think is incorrect.

00:20:34.980 --> 00:20:42.930 position:56%
I think that that's been somehow
the term that's favored is Baybayin,

00:20:42.930 --> 00:20:46.190
I think is the pronunciation.

00:20:46.190 --> 00:20:49.550
And the script, it's
an ancient script.

00:20:49.550 --> 00:20:53.500
And so, you know, when I
think about the way that Spain

00:20:53.500 --> 00:20:58.430
with the colonizing coming
forward and taking the culture

00:20:58.430 --> 00:21:02.300
that was there and molding it
in a way into the framework

00:21:02.300 --> 00:21:11.460 position:56%
of Catholicism, for instance, in the
Filipino history there is a term,

00:21:11.460 --> 00:21:16.620
"babaylan" the shaman or priestess.

00:21:16.620 --> 00:21:27.220
That they were very much a
part of the Filipino culture

00:21:27.220 --> 00:21:28.810
at the time before Spain.

00:21:28.810 --> 00:21:34.990
And so this idea of the
matriarch was in effect present.

00:21:34.990 --> 00:21:38.940
So when you talk to
Filipinos, Filipino-Americans

00:21:38.940 --> 00:21:45.510
about their faith, many will talk
about Mary -- the novena for Mary,

00:21:45.510 --> 00:21:52.910 position:56%
you know, the Virgin Mary very much,
you know, woven into that portion

00:21:52.910 --> 00:21:55.200 position:56%
of the Filipino-American experience.

00:21:55.200 --> 00:22:00.030
I mean, my father when he
relocated to Mobile, Alabama --

00:22:00.030 --> 00:22:03.230
he became friends with the
local priest and the first thing

00:22:03.230 --> 00:22:07.330
that he asked was, you know,
do you have a novena for Mary?

00:22:07.330 --> 00:22:09.270
And the priest was
like, no, we don't.

00:22:09.270 --> 00:22:11.640
And my dad like worked
with them to set this up

00:22:11.640 --> 00:22:15.580
and suddenly my dad said all these
Filipinos came out, you know,

00:22:15.580 --> 00:22:19.210
from nearby because they
heard about the novena

00:22:19.210 --> 00:22:20.940
and they wanted to
be a part of this.

00:22:20.940 --> 00:22:25.390
So that's how I kind of -- that's
how I see Spain still being woven

00:22:25.390 --> 00:22:30.920
into the cultures that
it's very much, you know,

00:22:30.920 --> 00:22:37.860 position:56%
the identity of faith for those who,
you know, who practice, it's there.

00:22:37.860 --> 00:22:41.530
The food, you know, the
empanadas, the different --

00:22:41.530 --> 00:22:44.450
and when you even look at --
again, I look at "lumpia,"

00:22:44.450 --> 00:22:45.990
