00:49:32.310 --> 00:49:33.610
of similar obstacles except that
he didn't resent this journey

00:49:33.610 --> 00:49:34.910
because it provided for his family.

00:49:34.910 --> 00:49:36.210
It also opened up numerous
opportunities

00:49:36.210 --> 00:49:37.510
that he wouldn't have never
had in the Philippines.

00:49:37.510 --> 00:49:38.810
But we still, like I -- you know,

00:49:38.810 --> 00:49:40.110
the beauty of the Rosetta Stone
-- do you know what it is?

00:49:40.110 --> 00:49:41.410
I have this Tagalog Rosetta Stone
program that I've listened to

00:49:41.410 --> 00:49:42.710
and have gone through
here and there.

00:49:42.710 --> 00:49:44.010
And I'm still trying
to like relearn things.

00:49:44.010 --> 00:49:45.310
And then I'll say something to
my dad and my dad will laugh.

00:49:45.310 --> 00:49:46.610
And he's like, you sound like
an American speaking Tagalog.

00:49:46.610 --> 00:49:47.910
And I'm like, that's exactly
what you wanted, right?

00:49:47.910 --> 00:49:49.210
Yeah [laughter].

00:49:49.210 --> 00:49:50.510
This is what -- yeah, here it is.

00:49:50.510 --> 00:49:51.810
But we can have fun with that.

00:49:51.810 --> 00:49:53.110
But I'd noticed that
like with our kids,

00:49:53.110 --> 00:49:54.410 position:56%
they've shown a huge interest in it.

00:49:54.410 --> 00:49:55.710 position:56%
So they still have him as a resource
but then we're hoping, you know,

00:49:55.710 --> 00:49:57.010
as time goes on, these other
communities will kind of emerge too

00:49:57.010 --> 00:49:58.310
so that they'll have access
to these Filipino-American

00:49:58.310 --> 00:49:59.610
communities elsewhere.

00:49:59.610 --> 00:50:00.910
When we go -- the food is
very much a part of our lives.

00:50:00.910 --> 00:50:02.210
I can cook it from scratch,
you know, "pan de sal,"

00:50:02.210 --> 00:50:03.510
the "pancit," you know, "lumpia."

00:50:03.510 --> 00:50:04.810
I'm brushing the wrappers.

00:50:04.810 --> 00:50:06.110
I'm teaching, you know, the kids
how to like paint on batter on so

00:50:06.110 --> 00:50:07.410
that it comes up like, you
know, like paper almost.

00:50:07.410 --> 00:50:08.710
So that's ingrained in us.

00:50:08.710 --> 00:50:12.580
But I think it's because I had that
initial connection with language

00:50:12.580 --> 00:50:18.470
and I hope that I'll be able to
[inaudible] this kind of carryon

00:50:18.470 --> 00:50:22.220
with my kids like they're
interested in [inaudible].

00:50:22.220 --> 00:50:23.710
&gt;&gt; Roberto Salazar: You have
some of your works with you?

00:50:23.710 --> 00:50:25.530
Do you have a favorite?

00:50:25.530 --> 00:50:29.560
&gt;&gt; Jon Pineda: Oh, I know
-- this is the trick.

00:50:29.560 --> 00:50:30.860
Yeah, yeah.

00:50:30.860 --> 00:50:32.160
&gt;&gt; Roberto Salazar: Yeah.

00:50:32.160 --> 00:50:33.460
&gt;&gt; Jon Pineda: I don't
have a favorite.

00:50:33.460 --> 00:50:34.760
It's not -- well, I, no --

00:50:34.760 --> 00:50:36.060
the favorite is always the
book I haven't written.

00:50:36.060 --> 00:50:37.360
Like it's the book that
I'm like working on, yeah.

00:50:37.360 --> 00:50:42.620
But no, I do -- there are some that
are -- you know, there are a few --

00:50:42.620 --> 00:50:44.710
would you mind if I read?

00:50:44.710 --> 00:50:46.010
&gt;&gt; Roberto Salazar: No, please do.

00:50:46.010 --> 00:50:47.310
&gt;&gt; Jon Pineda: Okay, yeah.

00:50:47.310 --> 00:50:53.090
Okay so this is poem that opens
<i>Birthmark </i>, my first collection.

00:50:53.090 --> 00:50:55.970
The poem is "Matamis."

00:50:59.040 --> 00:51:06.550
Matamis -- one summer in Pensacola,
I held an orange this way.

00:51:06.550 --> 00:51:11.370
Flesh hiding beneath the texture
of the rind and slipped my thumbs

00:51:11.370 --> 00:51:16.160
into its core and folded
it open like a book.

00:51:16.160 --> 00:51:19.750
When I held out the halves, the
juice seemed to trace the veins

00:51:19.750 --> 00:51:25.930
in my arms as it dripped down to my
elbows and darkened spots of sand.

00:51:25.930 --> 00:51:28.170
We were sitting on the beach then.

00:51:28.170 --> 00:51:32.600
The sun, spheres of
light within each piece.

00:51:32.600 --> 00:51:37.330
I remember thinking in Tagalog
the word, "matamis" is sweet

00:51:37.330 --> 00:51:40.920
in English though I
did not say it for fear

00:51:40.920 --> 00:51:43.880
of mispronouncing the language.

00:51:43.880 --> 00:51:49.230
Instead, I finished the fruit and
offered nothing except my silence.

00:51:49.230 --> 00:51:54.220
And my father who pried apart
another piece, breaking the globe

00:51:54.220 --> 00:51:58.610
in two, offered me half
meaning everything.

00:52:05.070 --> 00:52:06.370
&gt;&gt; Roberto Salazar: I'm checking.

00:52:06.370 --> 00:52:07.670
If you want, you [inaudible]?

00:52:07.670 --> 00:52:10.710
&gt;&gt; Jon Pineda: I meant to, okay.

00:52:10.710 --> 00:52:12.450
Let's see [laughter].

00:52:12.450 --> 00:52:14.370
This is always a good
one because in this,

00:52:14.370 --> 00:52:17.560
the speaker has hair [laughter].

00:52:17.560 --> 00:52:20.850
This is "Wrestling."

00:52:22.190 --> 00:52:25.270
Before the season, we
were already pissed.

00:52:25.270 --> 00:52:27.610
Our bodies tightening around ribs.

00:52:27.610 --> 00:52:32.090
Our eyes like panthers
sinking in the shadows.

00:52:32.090 --> 00:52:37.160
We had given up food, sweat until
the air around us was heavy.

00:52:37.160 --> 00:52:41.300
The only thing we cared
about was winning.

00:52:41.300 --> 00:52:45.100
At our first match, I wrestled
a guy I had met summers ago

00:52:45.100 --> 00:52:50.200
at a Filipino gathering, some
First Communion or baptism.

00:52:50.200 --> 00:52:54.520
By a manmade lake separating the
neighborhood in two where most

00:52:54.520 --> 00:52:58.840
of the children had wandered, a
few of the boys pinned my shoulders

00:52:58.840 --> 00:53:02.590
against the tree while
one punched me.

00:53:02.590 --> 00:53:07.050
I could say it was because
I was only half, a mestizo.

00:53:07.050 --> 00:53:09.360
But that would be too easy.

00:53:09.360 --> 00:53:13.360
We were just boys,
happy in our anger.

00:53:13.360 --> 00:53:17.280
When they let me go, their
eyes clouded as the lake.

00:53:17.280 --> 00:53:19.350
I didn't say a word.

00:53:19.350 --> 00:53:24.390
Years later, when I pulled the one
who had punched me down on the mat,

00:53:24.390 --> 00:53:29.070
I watched the clock as I locked
the breath inside his throat.

00:53:29.070 --> 00:53:30.900
He could have been my brother.

00:53:30.900 --> 00:53:34.160
His hair the same coarse
black strands.

00:53:34.160 --> 00:53:37.690
His face filled with my shadow.

00:53:37.690 --> 00:53:40.940
I held him there in
front of everyone.

00:53:44.040 --> 00:53:45.340
&gt;&gt; Roberto Salazar: Jon Pineda,

00:53:45.340 --> 00:53:48.600
trailblazing the Filipino-American
narrative.

00:53:48.600 --> 00:53:49.930
Thank you so much for
sharing with us.

00:53:49.930 --> 00:53:51.730
&gt;&gt; Jon Pineda: Thank you so much.

00:53:51.730 --> 00:53:56.380
[ Applause ]

